Scenario-Based Questions in Projects 
Common scenario questions interviewers ask once you finish explaining your project. 
Each answer is based on the Retail Sales Analytics Platform (Azure Databricks, Medallion architecture). Keep answers conversational — 60 to 90 seconds each. 
1. How Do You Handle Schema Evolution? 
What they are really asking: If a source adds/removes/renames a column tomorrow, does your pipeline break or handle it gracefully? 
Key Points to Cover 
• How you detect schema changes 
• What Delta Lake does automatically vs. what you control 
• Different evolution scenarios and how each is handled 
• How you communicate changes to downstream consumers 
Example Answer 
Schema evolution is something we handled at multiple layers depending on the type of change. 
Adding a new column (most common): 
We use mergeSchema = true in our Delta writes. So if the POS system adds a new column like discount_code, Spark automatically adds it to the Delta table schema on the next run. Old partitions show null for that column, new ones have the value. No pipeline failure, no manual intervention. 
Renaming or removing a column: 
This is more dangerous. We treat this as a breaking change. Our ingestion notebooks validate the incoming schema against a registered "expected schema" stored in a control table. If a column disappears, the job fails fast with a clear error message — it does not silently produce wrong data. We then raise a ticket, update the schema registry, and re-run. 
Data type change (e.g., amount goes from INT to DECIMAL): 
Delta Lake does not allow implicit type widening in all cases. We handle this by casting explicitly in the Silver transformation — so even if the source changes the type, our Silver logic normalises it before writing. We have unit tests that catch type mismatches on the fixture data. 
Communication to downstream: 
Any schema change to a Gold table triggers a Slack/Teams notification to the BI team so they know their Power BI reports may need updates. 




2. How Do You Add Data Quality Checks? 
What they are really asking: How do you ensure the data you are writing is actually correct, not just present?  
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
Key Points to Cover 
• Where in the pipeline DQ checks sit (Bronze, Silver, Gold) 
• What you check (nulls, ranges, referential integrity, row counts) 
• What happens when a check fails (stop vs. quarantine vs. alert) 
• Tools or frameworks used 
Example Answer 
We apply data quality checks at two layers — Bronze and Silver. 
At Bronze (structural checks): 
We validate that the file has the expected columns and that mandatory fields like transaction_id and store_id are not null. If the file is structurally broken, we reject the entire file and log it to a rejected_files table with a reason. The pipeline continues with other files. 
At Silver (business rule checks): 
This is where the real DQ logic lives. We check: 
• transaction_amount must be > 0 and < 1,000,000 (sanity range) 
• transaction_date must be within the last 90 days (late-arriving data threshold) 
• store_id must exist in the store_master reference table (referential integrity) 
• Row count of Silver output must be >= 90% of Bronze input (no silent data loss) 
Records that fail any of these checks go to a rejected_records Delta table with the exact rule that failed. The main pipeline continues with clean records — we do not stop the whole run for bad rows. 
At Gold (aggregate checks): 
We run a post-load assertion — if daily_sales_summary for today's date shows total revenue that is more than 3x or less than 30% of the 7-day average, we flag it as a data quality anomaly and alert the team, even if the job technically succeeded. 
For the framework, we use a mix of custom PySpark assertions and great_expectations for the more complex rule sets. 









3. How Do You Backfill Data — Full Historical or Time-Defined? 
What they are really asking: If something went wrong for the last 30 days, or if you need to load 3 years of history, how do you do it without breaking things? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Full historical backfill approach 
• Partial / time-range backfill 
• How you avoid duplicates during re-processing 
• Performance considerations for large backfills 
Example Answer Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
We have two backfill scenarios — full historical load and partial date-range backfill. 
Full historical backfill (e.g., first-time load or complete rebuild): 
We parameterise our pipelines with a start_date and end_date. For a full backfill, we pass start_date = 1900-01-01 (or the actual earliest date in the source) and end_date = today. The ingestion job processes data in daily or weekly chunks using a loop — we never try to load everything in one giant Spark job, as that causes memory and shuffle issues. 
the history is untouched. This makes the backfill safe to re-run if it fails halfway. 
Partial / time-range backfill (e.g., fix the last 30 days): 
We have a utility notebook called backfill_runner that accepts start_date and end_date as widgets. It queries the audit control table to identify which batch IDs to reprocess and triggers Silver and Gold jobs only for those date partitions. Bronze is skipped if the raw files are already in the landing zone. 
Avoiding duplicates: 
All Gold writes use MERGE INTO keyed on business keys + date. So running the backfill twice produces the same result — updates in place, no duplicates. 
Performance: 
For large historical backfills (like 2+ years), we increase the cluster to a larger auto-scaling range and run the backfill over a weekend to avoid competing with production workloads. We also enable Delta's OPTIMIZE and ZORDER after the backfill completes to restore query performance. 
4. What Are the Strategies Available for CDC Loads? 
What they are really asking: How do you capture and process only changed data from source systems instead of reloading everything every time? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Watermark / high-watermark approach 
• Database CDC (log-based) using tools like Debezium 
• Full load with deduplication 
• Soft deletes vs. hard deletes handling 
Example Answer Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
We used three different CDC strategies in our project depending on the source system's capabilities. Strategy 1 — Watermark / High-watermark (most common): 
For SQL Server (POS) and Oracle (ERP), we track the last successfully loaded max(updated_at) or max(transaction_date) in an audit control table. On each run, we query WHERE updated_at > last_watermark. Simple, reliable, and works without any source-side changes. The risk is if a record gets updated with a backdated timestamp — we would miss it. We mitigated this with a small overlap window (we go back 15 minutes before the watermark to catch late updates). 
Strategy 2 — Log-based CDC (Debezium / Kafka): 
For a real-time stream we added later, we used Debezium to read the Oracle redo log and publish INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE events to Kafka topics. Spark Structured Streaming consumed these topics and applied them to our Delta Silver tables using MERGE INTO. This is the most accurate CDC method — captures every change including deletes — but it requires DBA access to enable log mining on the source. 
Strategy 3 — Full load with deduplication: 
For smaller reference tables like store_master (< 50K rows), we do a full load every night and use MERGE INTO to apply changes. Cheaper to implement than CDC, and the small table size means it's fast enough. 
Handling deletes: 
For soft deletes (source sets is_deleted = true), we propagate the flag through to Silver and filter them out at Gold. For hard deletes (row physically removed from source), we only catch them with log-based CDC. Watermark-based approaches do not see hard deletes — we documented this as a known limitation. 
5. How Do You Make Your Pipeline More Scalable? 
What they are really asking: If data volume doubles or triples, does your pipeline still work or does it fall over? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Auto-scaling compute 
• Incremental processing (avoid full scans) 
• Partitioning strategy 
• Parallelism tuning 
• Design choices that allow horizontal scaling 
Example Answer  
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
Scalability was a first-class concern in our design. Here is how we addressed it at each level. Compute — auto-scaling clusters: 
Our Databricks Job Cluster scales from 4 to 12 workers automatically. During a Black Friday data spike (3x normal volume), the cluster scaled up without any manual intervention and the pipeline still completed within SLA. 
Incremental processing: 
the new daily slice. So even as the total table grows to years of history, each individual run touches the same small volume. 
Partitioning: 
All Silver and Gold tables are partitioned by sale_date. Queries from Power BI only scan the relevant date partition — they never full-scan a 3-year table. We also apply ZORDER BY (store_id, product_id) on the Gold tables for fast filtered reads. 
Parallel ingestion: 
The three ingestion jobs (POS, ERP, CRM) run in parallel in the Databricks Workflow DAG. We do not run them sequentially, so ingestion time is bounded by the slowest source, not the sum of all three. 
File batching at ingestion: 
The Step Functions workflow groups pending files into configurable batches and launches multiple Glue/Spark jobs in parallel. If we get 5,000 files instead of 500, we just spin up more parallel jobs — the design is horizontally scalable by nature. 
What would break at extreme scale: 
The MERGE INTO operation on very large Gold tables can become expensive. At high scale we would consider partitioned merges — merging one date partition at a time rather than the full table. 
6. How Can You Prove That Your Pipeline Is More Secure? 
What they are really asking: Walk me through your actual security controls — not just "we used Key Vault". 
Key Points to Cover 
• Secret management (no hardcoded credentials) 
• Authentication and access control (RBAC, managed identity) 
• Network security (VNet, private endpoints) 
• Data-level security (column masking, row-level security) 
• Audit trail 
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
I can walk through this at four levels — secrets, access, network, and data. 
Secrets — zero hardcoded credentials: 
Every credential (DB passwords, API tokens, storage account keys) is stored in Azure Key Vault. Databricks accesses them via a Service Principal with the Key Vault Reader role. There is literally no password or key anywhere in the codebase. We enforce this with a pre-commit hook that scans for common secret patterns and blocks the commit if any are found. 
Access control — principle of least privilege: 
Storage access uses Azure Managed Identity — no storage account keys are exposed. RBAC is applied at each layer: 
• Bronze: only the ingestion service principal can write here. Analysts have no access. 
• Silver: data engineers can read/write. Analysts cannot. 
• Gold: read-only for the BI team and analysts. They cannot see raw or PII data. 
Network — no public exposure: 
The Databricks workspace is deployed inside an Azure VNet with private endpoints. The ADLS Gen2 storage account has public network access disabled — it only accepts connections from within the VNet. There is no way to access the data from the public internet. 
Data-level — PII handling: 
PII columns from the CRM (customer email, phone number, SSN) are SHA-256 hashed at the Silver layer. The original values never reach Gold. Analysts only ever see hashed values. 
Audit trail: 
Delta Lake maintains a full transaction log — every write, merge, and delete is recorded. Azure Monitor captures all Databricks workspace activity. We can answer "who accessed what data and when" for any compliance audit. 
7. How Do You Handle PII or Sensitive Data? 
What they are really asking: Do you have a concrete strategy, or did you just "mask some columns"? 
Key Points to Cover 
• What counts as PII in your project 
• Where masking/hashing happens in the pipeline 
• Tokenisation vs. hashing vs. encryption 
• Access controls around raw PII 
• Compliance alignment (GDPR, CCPA, etc.) 
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
We had three categories of sensitive data — customer PII, financial data, and employee data. Identification of PII: 
We worked with the data governance team to tag PII columns in the AWS Glue / Databricks Unity Catalog. Any column tagged as PII is automatically subject to masking rules. This gives us a central registry — if a new PII column is added to a source table, it gets tagged and the masking applies automatically on the next schema refresh. 
Masking approach: 
For columns like customer email and phone number — we use SHA-256 one-way hashing at the Silver layer. The hash is deterministic, so you can still join tables on the hashed value (e.g., count loyalty points per customer) without exposing the actual email. The raw value is never written to Silver or Gold. For financial account numbers — we use format-preserving tokenisation. The token looks like a real account number (same length, same format) so existing downstream systems do not break, but it is meaningless outside the tokenisation service. 
Access to raw PII: 
The Bronze layer (where raw PII exists) is restricted to the ingestion service principal and the DBA team only. Data engineers work with Silver and Gold where PII is already masked. We have zero exceptions to this — even the data engineering lead cannot read Bronze in production without going through an access request workflow. 
Compliance: 
For GDPR right-to-erasure requests, we have a documented process — we identify the customer's hashed key, delete or overwrite all records with that key in Silver and Gold using Delta Lake's DELETE operation, and run VACUUM to remove the physical files. We tested this process and it completes in under 2 hours for a single customer. 
8. What Are the Different Strategies to Read JDBC or Tabular Data? 
What they are really asking: Do you just do spark.read.jdbc(...) and hope for the best, or do you know how to tune it for large tables? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Single partition read (simple, slow for large tables) 
• Multi-partition read using numPartitions + partitionColumn 
• Predicate pushdown 
• Incremental vs. full load 
• Connection pooling and driver considerations 
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
Reading from JDBC sources at scale has several gotchas. Here is how we approach it. 
Strategy 1 — Single partition (default, only for small tables): 
spark.read.jdbc(url, table, properties) opens a single JDBC connection and reads everything sequentially. Fine for the store_master table (50K rows) but completely unsuitable for sales_transactions (2M rows/day). All the data would flow through one executor — no parallelism. 
Strategy 2 — Multi-partition read (our main approach for large tables): 
We use partitionColumn, lowerBound, upperBound, and numPartitions to split the read across multiple o
parallel JDBC connections. Spark creates numPartitions tasks, each reading a range of the partition column. We typically use a numeric ID or a date column as the partition column. For our POS transactions, we partition on transaction_id with 20 partitions — Spark opens 20 parallel connections to SQL Server and reads in parallel. 
Strategy 3 — Predicate pushdown for incremental loads: 
We always pass a WHERE clause using the predicates parameter or via a query string — (SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE transaction_date = '2024-01-15') AS t. This pushes the filter down to the database — the database does the filtering, not Spark. Only the relevant rows travel over the network. 
Strategy 4 — Fetch size tuning: 
By default the JDBC fetch size is very small (often 10 rows per round trip). We set fetchsize = 10000 in the JDBC properties. This dramatically reduces round trips and speeds up the read. 
Strategy 5 — Using database views or stored procedures: 
For complex joins or business logic that is cheaper to run on the source DB, we read from a pre-built database view rather than joining multiple tables in Spark. The DB does what it is good at, Spark does what it is good at. 
Driver and connection pool considerations: 
We stage the JDBC driver JAR on the cluster init script. For Oracle, we use the thin driver (ojdbc8.jar). We also set connection timeout and retry settings in the JDBC properties to handle transient source DB unavailability without crashing the job. 
9. What Are Your Steps for Debugging a Production Job with Minimum Downtime? 
What they are really asking: Do you have a structured approach, or do you just randomly poke at things and hope the problem goes away? 
Key Points to Cover 
• First response (check logs, not the code) 
• Isolation (which step failed, not the whole pipeline) 
• Root cause categories (data issue, resource issue, code issue, dependency issue) 
• Fix and re-run strategy 
• Post-mortem 
Example Answer 
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
We follow a structured 5-step approach to minimise the time users are impacted. 
Step 1 — Triage (2 minutes): 
Check the Databricks Workflows UI and the audit log table immediately. We look at: which specific task failed, at what step, what was the error message, and how many records were processed before failure. This tells us instantly whether it is a data issue (e.g., bad file), an infrastructure issue (e.g., driver OOM), or a code issue (e.g., null pointer in a transformation). 
Step 2 — Isolate (5 minutes): 
We never re-run the full pipeline blindly. We identify the exact failed task (e.g., silver_transform_pos) and check the Spark UI for the failed stage — the error message at the executor level is usually more specific than the driver-level error. We also check Log Analytics for the full stack trace. 
Step 3 — Categorise and fix: 
• Data issue (e.g., a file with an unexpected format): Fix the file or add it to a quarantine list and re-run. Pipeline continues without that file. 
• Resource issue (e.g., OOM, shuffle spill): Increase driver memory or shuffle partitions in the job config and re-trigger. 
• Dependency issue (e.g., upstream source was late): Just re-trigger once the dependency is resolved. No code change needed. 
• Code issue (e.g., logic bug on an edge case): Fix in a feature branch, test locally with a small reproduction dataset, deploy to prod via the normal CI/CD pipeline — or, if time-critical, use a hotfix branch with expedited approval. 
Step 4 — Re-run safely: 
Because our jobs are idempotent, we re-run only the failed task and the downstream tasks — not the entire pipeline. The audit control table tracks where we left off, so we never reprocess what already succeeded. 
Step 5 — Post-mortem: 
For any failure that caused an SLA breach, we write a brief post-mortem: root cause, timeline, fix applied, and what we are adding to prevent recurrence (a new DQ check, a better error message, an alert threshold). This goes into Confluence so the whole team learns from it. 
