Here are three real issues we dealt with in production. 
Issue 1 — Salesforce API token expiry causing silent partial loads: 
The CRM ingestion job was completing without errors, but we noticed the customer record count was lower than expected. The API token had expired mid-run — Salesforce was returning HTTP 401 for the latter pages of results, but our error handling was catching the exception and logging it at WARNING level, not ERROR. The job finished but only loaded the first few pages. 
job. Added a row count check that compares today's ingested count against the 7-day average. Now if count drops by more than 20%, the job is flagged even if it completes. 
Issue 2 — Delta MERGE causing OOM on the Gold layer: 
Three months after go-live, the daily MERGE INTO daily_sales_summary started timing out and crashing with OutOfMemory on the driver. The Gold table had grown to 18 months of data and the MERGE was scanning the full table. 
Fix: We switched to a partitioned merge — instead of merging the full table, we added WHEN sale_date = current_date() to the MERGE condition. This tells Delta to only scan and merge the relevant date partition. Job time dropped from 45 minutes back to 8 minutes. We also ran OPTIMIZE and ZORDER on the table to clean up small files that had accumulated. 
Issue 3 — Source SQL Server timeout during business hours: 
The POS ingestion job ran at midnight but one day it was retriggered manually at 2 PM (after a failure). The JDBC read timed out because the source SQL Server was under heavy load from business users during the day. 
Fix: Added a JDBC queryTimeout = 300 and loginTimeout = 60 property, and configured 3 automatic retries with a 15-minute backoff. Also added a check — if the current time is between 8 AM and 6 PM, the manual re-trigger sends a warning alert before proceeding so the on-call engineer is aware it may impact source DB performance. 
11. What Are the Limitations of Your Project? 
What they are really asking: Are you self-aware enough to know where your solution breaks down, or do you think it is perfect? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Known technical limitations 
• Scale limits 
• Architectural trade-offs 
• Things you would change with more time/budget 
Example Answer 
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
We are transparent about our limitations — knowing them is as important as knowing the strengths. 1. Watermark-based CDC does not catch hard deletes: 
If a record is physically deleted from the source SQL Server, we have no way to detect it with watermark-based ingestion. The record stays in our Silver and Gold tables permanently. We documented this and the business accepted it — most of their "deletes" are soft deletes (a flag is set). For true hard-delete compliance we would need log-based CDC like Debezium. 
2. MERGE performance degrades at very large scale: 
Example Answer o
Our MERGE INTO on Gold tables works well up to about 2 years of data. Beyond that, even with partitioned merges, the operation slows down. At 5+ years of history we would need to archive older partitions to a cold storage tier and only keep rolling 2 years in the active Gold table. 
3. No real-time capability: 
The pipeline is batch-only — daily refresh. If the business ever needs intraday or real-time analytics, the architecture would need a significant change — introducing Kafka and Spark Structured Streaming. The current design was built for daily batch and is not easily extensible to sub-hourly without rebuilding the ingestion layer. 
4. Databricks Workflows is not a full orchestration tool: 
For simple linear DAGs it works well. But for complex, cross-pipeline dependencies (e.g., Pipeline B in Domain 2 depends on Pipeline A in Domain 1 finishing) we had to build our own dependency tracking in the Aurora control table. A dedicated tool like Apache Airflow would handle this more elegantly. 
5. Cost visibility is limited at the domain level: 
We can see total cluster costs but cannot easily break down costs per domain or per pipeline. This makes it hard to do accurate chargeback to individual business units. 
12. What Are Your Data Lifecycle Policies and How Did You Implement Them? 
What they are really asking: Do you just accumulate data forever, or do you have a plan for what happens to old data? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Retention policy per layer (Bronze/Silver/Gold) 
• How deletion is implemented (Delta DELETE + VACUUM) 
• Archival to cold storage 
• Compliance-driven retention (GDPR 7-year financial records, etc.) 
We have a tiered retention policy, different per layer, driven by both compliance requirements and cost. Bronze (raw data) — 90 days: 
Raw files are business-critical for re-processing but expensive to store long-term. We retain the last 90 days of raw files in ADLS Gen2 hot tier. After 90 days, an Azure Lifecycle Management policy automatically moves files to the cool tier (cheaper) and deletes them at 180 days. This is automated — no manual cleanup needed. 
Silver (cleaned data) — 3 years: 
Silver tables are retained for 3 years in active Delta format. After 3 years, we run OPTIMIZE to compact them, o
then move the Parquet files to the cold tier. The Delta log is retained so time-travel queries still work for audit purposes. 
Gold (aggregated/business data) — 7 years: 
Financial regulations require us to retain aggregated sales data for 7 years. Gold tables stay in hot/cool tier for 2 years of active querying, then move to the cold archive tier. We use Delta's shallow clone to create a lightweight reference to the archived data without duplicating storage. 
Delta transaction log retention: 
By default Delta retains 30 days of transaction log. We increased this to 90 days for Silver and Gold (delta.logRetentionDuration = interval 90 days) to support longer time-travel windows for audits. 
Implementation: 
• Azure Lifecycle Management policies handle the automated tier transitions 
• A weekly Databricks job runs VACUUM on all tables with the appropriate retention period to clean up old file versions 
• Compliance-triggered deletions (GDPR erasure) are handled manually via a documented runbook and verified by the data governance team before execution 
