15. What Optimisations Did You Perform in the Project? 
What they are really asking: Did you just build it and forget it, or did you actively make it better over time? 
Key Points to Cover 
• Performance optimisations (query speed, job duration) 
• Cost optimisations (compute, storage) 
• Reliability optimisations (retry logic, idempotency) 
• Developer experience optimisations (faster debugging, better logging) 
Example Answer 
Scenario-Based Questions in Projects DataArchitectStudio 
Optimisation was an ongoing activity, not a one-time task. Here are the most impactful ones. Performance — Partitioned MERGE: 
Three months after go-live, our Gold MERGE operations were taking 45 minutes because they were scanning the entire table. We added a date partition filter to the MERGE condition — WHEN sale_date = current_date(). Job time dropped from 45 minutes to 8 minutes. No schema or logic change needed. 
Performance — Small file compaction: 
Queries from analysts were slow because Spark was opening thousands of file handles. We added a weekly OPTIMIZE job on all Silver tables using Databricks' built-in OPTIMIZE command with ZORDER BY (store_id, product_id). Query times from Power BI improved by 60%. 
Cost — Spot instances for workers: 
We switched worker nodes from on-demand to Azure Spot instances. This reduced compute cost by approximately 60% for worker nodes. We kept the driver on on-demand to avoid job failure if the driver gets preempted. Total compute cost dropped by ~40%. 
Cost — Job cluster instead of all-purpose cluster: 
Initially we ran everything on an all-purpose cluster that stayed up 24/7. We switched to Job Clusters — they spin up fresh per run and terminate after. This eliminated ~18 hours of idle cluster time per day. 
Reliability — Idempotent writes: 
Early versions used INSERT INTO for Gold writes. After a re-run caused duplicate records, we migrated all Gold writes to MERGE INTO with business key deduplication. Re-runs are now completely safe. 
Reliability — Parallel ingestion: 
Originally the three ingestion jobs ran sequentially (POS → ERP → CRM). We refactored the Databricks Workflow to run them in parallel. End-to-end pipeline time dropped from 3.5 hours to 1.8 hours — staying well within the 7 AM SLA. 
Developer experience — Structured audit logging: 
Early on, debugging a failure meant reading raw Spark logs — painful and slow. We added structured JSON logging to a Delta audit table. Now any failure can be diagnosed in under 5 minutes by querying SELECT * FROM control.pipeline_audit_log WHERE status = 'FAILED' ORDER BY start_time DESC LIMIT 10. 
